snippet.textDisplay: Many of the franchise movies that are now called "bad" aren't really being judged on quality in the largest sense so much as how they fail to live up to the nostalgia expectations of fans, without any real analysis of just how good "the good ol' stuff" really was. Saying things like "I grew up with" Terminator or Star Wars or The Lion King and calling them "classic" isn't really the same thing as calling them great film. We switched to a predominantly junk food movie diet at just about the same time that studios, knowing the quality of what they were making, started wanting to recoup the cost of production in the first 72 hours after release and were so worried about reviewers releasing "spoilers". People will get upset at Scorsese for saying that the MCU isn't cinema (in the sense that HE's using the word cinema), yet no one will argue that the MCU is actually classic film either.
